<cell id="cell-0"><language>kotlin</language>// Kotlin notebook
import jline.*
import jline.lang.*
import jline.lang.nodes.*
import jline.lang.processes.*
import jline.lang.constant.*
import jline.solvers.mva.*
import jline.util.matrix.*</cell id="cell-0">
<cell id="cell-1"><language>kotlin</language>// Define the workflow
val wf = Workflow("ErlangWorkflow")</cell id="cell-1">
<cell id="cell-2"><language>kotlin</language>// Add activities with Erlang distributions (SCV < 1)
val A = wf.addActivity("A", Erlang.fitMeanAndOrder(2.0, 4))  // 4 phases, SCV=0.25
val B = wf.addActivity("B", Erlang.fitMeanAndOrder(3.0, 2))  // 2 phases, SCV=0.5
val C = wf.addActivity("C", Exp.fitMean(1.0))                // 1 phase, SCV=1.0</cell id="cell-2">
<cell id="cell-3"><language>kotlin</language>// Define serial precedence
wf.addPrecedence(Workflow.serial(A, B, C))</cell id="cell-3">
<cell id="cell-4"><language>kotlin</language>// Convert to phase-type distribution
val ph = wf.toPH()</cell id="cell-4">
<cell id="cell-5"><language>kotlin</language>// Display results
println("Erlang Workflow: A -> B -> C")
println("Activity A: Erlang(mean=2.0, phases=4), SCV=0.25")
println("Activity B: Erlang(mean=3.0, phases=2), SCV=0.50")
println("Activity C: Exp(mean=1.0), SCV=1.00")
println("Expected total mean: ${2.0 + 3.0 + 1.0}")
println("Computed PH mean: ${ph.mean}")
println("Computed PH SCV: ${ph.sCV}")
println("Number of phases: ${ph.subgenerator.getNumRows()}")</cell id="cell-5">
<cell id="cell-6"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## Workflow with Erlang Distribution

A workflow using Erlang distributions for lower variability.

**Workflow:** A -> B -> C

This example demonstrates:
- Using Erlang distributions with different numbers of phases
- Erlang distributions provide lower variability (SCV < 1) compared to exponential (SCV = 1)
- The number of phases controls the variability: more phases = lower SCV
- Erlang(k) has SCV = 1/k, so Erlang(4) has SCV=0.25, Erlang(2) has SCV=0.5
- The phase-type representation combines all activity phases into a single distribution</cell id="cell-6"></cell>